	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>GradualGames</b> [ Thu Jan 07, 2010 8:44 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Simple question about modern NES emulators</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />My focus is on my homebrew game, so I don't really know anything about how emulators work. But I was wondering a bit ago how sprites are handled and wondered if any modern emulators take advantage of hardware acceleration at least for sprites or perhaps even for the background, or if most emulators just use a framebuffer and have hand-rolled code for writing all pixels, background and sprite, to it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Disch</b> [ Thu Jan 07, 2010 9:14 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Most emus do everything in software, pixel at a time.
<br />
<br />The NES does too many timing sensitive raster tricks to effectively take advantage of hardware acceleration.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Dwedit</b> [ Thu Jan 07, 2010 9:29 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />PocketNES on the GBA uses the GBA's hardware to render the background and sprites.  NesDS for the Nintendo Ds is based on PocketNES, so it does the same as well.
<br />
<br />That seems to be the way most emulators on the GBA/DS work, they use the 2D hardware instead of framebuffers.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Fri Jan 08, 2010 1:44 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The GBA can get away with that because the GBA's video hardware is one of the many VDPs <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=5039" class="postlink">heavily inspired by Texas Instruments' TMS9918 VDP</a>, just like the video hardware in NES, Game Boy, PC Engine, and Super NES. Special effects for one translate fairly cleanly to the others. And each of the DS's 2D cores is essentially a GBA PPU.
<br />
<br />The PC, on the other hand, has more of a Williams model: a dumb frame buffer filled by either a soft blitter or more traditional blitter hardware. The blitter hardware is different enough from the TMS9918 derivatives that the techniques don't translate well.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


